If you didn't know why nasdaq stock fell of yesterday here's the summary:

&#x200B;

>Nasdaq Inc (NASDAQ:NDAQ) was met with a severe blow as the market opened today, with its shares plunging a staggering 10% in response to the company's recent announcement of a groundbreaking $10.5 billion acquisition deal with software investment firm Adenza. The market's reaction to Nasdaq's largest-ever acquisition sent shockwaves through the industry, causing widespread selling pressure and rattling investor confidence.

&#x200B;

>The substantial decline resulted in NDAQ shares opening significantly lower, trading just above their year-to-date lows of approximately $52, a level reminiscent of the mid-March slump. Despite a modest recovery of 10% over the past three months from those lows, Nasdaq's stock encountered formidable resistance at its 160-day moving average, preventing any sustained upward momentum.

&#x200B;

>Despite the downward pressure, short-term options traders have demonstrated a prevailing call-bias, as indicated by NDAQ's Schaeffer's put/call open interest ratio (SOIR) of 0.46. This ratio, lower than 95% of readings from the past year, suggests that traders hold bullish expectations, anticipating a possible recovery in the stock's price in the near future.  
>  
>The market's reaction to Nasdaq's sharp decline has led to a compelling situation for options traders. Options on NDAQ are currently priced relatively affordably, with NDAQ's Schaeffer's Volatility Index (SVI) reading at 19%, placing it in the very low 3rd percentile compared to readings from the past 12 months. This low SVI implies that options traders are factoring in lower-than-expected levels of volatility, indicating a perceived stability in the stock's future performance.

&#x200B;

Charles Schwab will be disclosing its next liquidity update next month on a Tuesday.  Investors will be looking into whether core assets have increased or not. If the new core assets brought into Charles Schwab during May is less than the total amount of deposits that left the US banking system for the week of 07/05 - 07/09, the stock will sell off just as usual.

&#x200B;

If Charles Schwab brings in about 40-47 billion dollars in new capital similar to February, I expect the stock to rally, even if this number is below the amount of deposits gained within the US banking system.

&#x200B;

Charles Schwab is a full service broker with Chase Bank as an agent for deposits/clearing. It is expected to completely absorb T.D. Ameritrade by Labor Day.
